{"id":166,"date":"2009-04-11T14:56:57","date_gmt":"2009-04-11T14:56:57","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.wordsforaplanet.net\/?p=166"},"modified":"2015-08-01T19:03:27","modified_gmt":"2015-08-01T19:03:27","slug":"architectural-design","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/","title":{"rendered":"architectural design"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><strong>A new kind of architecture<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>John Christophers, the <a href=\"\/about\/john-christophers\/\">architect of zero carbon house<\/a>, says:<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;My\u00a0architectural design ideas were not\u00a0imposed arbitrarily, but\u00a0grew out of the green agenda.\u00a0Some people run away from thinking about climate change, finding it as all too depressing, while some architects see sustainable building as a negative drag, imposing unwelcome constraints on their designs.\u00a0 I take the opposite view. \u00a0Of course good architecture should work as beautiful design; but rather than restricting, I believe a deep understanding of sustainability can help to generate a new kind of architecture that uses materials and light in creative and inspiring ways.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p><em>\u201cDesigning for climate change can become a positive \u2026 regenerative force in architecture, with buildings responding to rather than excluding climate.\u00a0\u00a0 Just as J.M.W.Turner transformed the polluted skies of London and Venice into great works of art, so we need to turn climate change into a new architecture.\u201d<\/em>\u00a0\u00a0(Brian Edwards, Professor of Architecture, Copenhagen).<\/p>\n<p>For further details of the way\u00a0daylight and materials are used as a regenerative force in architecture in the design of zero carbon house see:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"\/design\/light\/\">light and the ash tree<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"\/design\/materials\/\">materials<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"\/design\/ventilation\/\">ventilation<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3><strong>A walk through<\/strong><\/h3>\n<p><strong>zero carbon house<\/strong> is an enlargement of an existing 1840 two-up, two-down terraced house. \u00a0We extended it to the side, where there was a space that had been used to park a car and we added a storey at the top.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-2' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/original-1840-semi\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Original-1840-semi-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"Front of the zero carbon house, Birmingham when it was an 1840s semi\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-2-3413\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-2-3413'>\n\t\t\t\tThe original 1840s semi\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-40\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Front-view-of-semi-detached-house-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-2-3232\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-2-3232'>\n\t\t\t\tThe zero carbon house\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>Our ground floor is open-plan, creating a variety of different spaces: kitchen, dining and a tall top-lit living room, allowing high quality natural daylight to flood through the house.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-4' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/homes-architect-john-christophers-zero-carbon-house-located-in-balsall-heath-birmingham-9\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Open-plan-floor-300-x-453-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-4-3419\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Open-plan-floor-300-x-453-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Open-plan-floor-300-x-453.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-4-3419'>\n\t\t\t\tOpen plan living area\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon portrait'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-41\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/07\/Top-lit-living-area-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"Open plan living area in zero carbon house with John and Theo on sofa and Jo beside\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-4-3268\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-4-3268'>\n\t\t\t\tTop light on living area\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon portrait'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/natural-light-floods-in\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Natural-light-floods-in-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-4-3269\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-4-3269'>\n\t\t\t\tNatural light floods in\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>The windows go from the floor to the ceiling, so we never feel far from nature and enjoy the low winter sun in our home. \u00a0With the combination of the roof-lights and openings with mirrored linings, visitors often comment on the quality of the natural light.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-6' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/bathroom-by-stanton-950-x-500\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Bathroom-by-Stanton-950-x-500-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-6-3429\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-6-3429'>\n\t\t\t\tThe use of windows and mirrors\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>The modern work doubles the space on the ground and first floors and adds a long studio, called the Long room, on the new second floor.\u00a0 The Long room\u00a0roof is at the right height, pitch and orientation for the solar panels, which provide so much of the house\u2019s renewable energy needs.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-8' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/resources\/art-installation-2010\/centre-and-circumference-by-jake-lever\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2010\/03\/Centre-and-Circumference-by-Jake-Lever-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-8-3011\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-8-3011'>\n\t\t\t\tThe Long room\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon portrait'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-24\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Stairs-in-the-Zero-Carbon-House-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-8-3204\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-8-3204'>\n\t\t\t\tOpen treads \n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>The top-lit radiating stair is compressed between the existing Victorian brickwork and the gently curved new walls that enclose it.\u00a0 The stair\u2019s open treads allow light to filter down, with views through to give a feeling of openness.<\/p>\n<p>We have shuttered openings to the stair and bedrooms.\u00a0 The shutters may be closed or open to change the character of the internal spaces, to give extra daylight, and to assist natural summer ventilation. They have also been used as stages for puppet shows.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-10' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-44\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Shutters-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"Shutters in the Long room at zero carbon house, Birmingham\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-10-3439\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-10-3439'>\n\t\t\t\tShutters in the Long room\n\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/shutter-looking-down-to-lounge-500-x-500\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/08\/Shutter-looking-down-to-lounge-500-x-500-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"Shutter opening in the zero carbon house, Birmingham\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-10-3583\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/08\/Shutter-looking-down-to-lounge-500-x-500-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/08\/Shutter-looking-down-to-lounge-500-x-500-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/08\/Shutter-looking-down-to-lounge-500-x-500.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-10-3583'>\n\t\t\t\tOpening to living area\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>The first floor has a bedroom with an oriel window looking up and down the street, and a further three bedrooms.\u00a0 Two of these, within the old part of the house, have openings overlooking the double-height living area.<\/p>\n<p>On the top floor a projecting timber-lined dormer window frames the wide view north to the city centre.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-12' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/home\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-35\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2008\/12\/Oriel-window-500-x-500-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-12-2859\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2008\/12\/Oriel-window-500-x-500-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2008\/12\/Oriel-window-500-x-500-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2008\/12\/Oriel-window-500-x-500.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-12-2859'>\n\t\t\t\tOriel window\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/riba-award-winning-2010-home-in-the-centre-of-birmingham-36\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/06\/Tulips-in-the-alcove-looking-out-to-Tindal-St-500-x-500-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"Tulips in a vase on the window sill of the alcove of the studio, zero carbon house, Birmingham with view of Tindal St\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-12-2888\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/06\/Tulips-in-the-alcove-looking-out-to-Tindal-St-500-x-500-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/06\/Tulips-in-the-alcove-looking-out-to-Tindal-St-500-x-500-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/06\/Tulips-in-the-alcove-looking-out-to-Tindal-St-500-x-500.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-12-2888'>\n\t\t\t\tTimber-lined dormer window\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>Seen from the front, the facade of the 1840 house remains untouched while the new dormer window bridges the different roof heights.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Modern green design<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>Birmingham City Council planners welcomed the modern green design, filling a vacant gap in the street, and using materials &#8211; reclaimed imperial bricks, white render and 30 degree pitched slate grey roofs &#8211; in sympathy with the surroundings.<\/p>\n<div id='gallery-14' class='gallery galleryid-166 gallery-columns-3 gallery-size-thumbnail'><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon landscape'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/outside-materials\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Outside-materials-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-14-3437\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-14-3437'>\n\t\t\t\tSympathetic materials\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure><figure class='gallery-item'>\n\t\t\t<div class='gallery-icon portrait'>\n\t\t\t\t<a href='https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/design\/architectural-design\/seen-from-the-street-800-x-805\/'><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Seen-from-the-street-800-x-805-150x150.jpg\" class=\"attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail\" alt=\"\" aria-describedby=\"gallery-14-3435\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Seen-from-the-street-800-x-805-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Seen-from-the-street-800-x-805-298x300.jpg 298w, https:\/\/zerocarbonhousebirmingham.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2009\/04\/Seen-from-the-street-800-x-805.jpg 800w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/a>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption class='wp-caption-text gallery-caption' id='gallery-14-3435'>\n\t\t\t\tModern green design\n\t\t\t\t<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\n<p>The dormer and oriel windows relate to the rich roof-scape of surrounding Arts &amp; Crafts houses in Moseley and Balsall Heath. Although the scale and materials are contextual, the architecture is modern, not pretending to be Victorian pastiche.<\/p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #8fb258;\">You might also be interested in:<\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><a title=\"Gallery\" href=\"\/design\/gallery\/\">gallery<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"\/design\/inspirations\/\">inspirations<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"\/about\/john-christophers\/\">meet the architect<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a title=\"Design\" href=\"\/design\/\">design<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"\/awards-media\/awards\/\">awards<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>A new kind of architecture John Christophers, the architect of zero carbon house, says: &#8220;My\u00a0architectural design ideas were not\u00a0imposed arbitrarily,&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":2811,"parent":2030,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","template":"","meta":{"footnotes":""},"class_list":["post-166","page","type-page",